  "response_text": "The megaherbivore population exhibits a deterministic trajectory toward extinction under the specified parameter configuration. Beginning at approximately 167 individuals, the population undergoes a rapid collapse during the initial 500 ticks, declining by over 90% to reach low double-digit or single-digit numbers. This steep descent is characterized by strongly significant decreasing trends with steep negative slopes across consecutive temporal windows.\n\nFollowing the initial collapse, the system enters an extended low-density persistence phase spanning approximately ticks 500 to 1500, marked by high volatility and oscillatory behavior with a dominant period of approximately 63 ticks. During this interval, the population fluctuates between minima of roughly 2–9 individuals and maxima reaching approximately 7–11 individuals, with notable local peaks occurring at tick 730 (approximately 11 individuals), tick 709 (approximately 9 individuals), tick 803 (approximately 7 individuals), and tick 820 (approximately 7 individuals). These oscillations represent demographic fluctuations under intense predation pressure, interspersed with valleys at ticks 708, 729, 802, and 819 where populations dip to approximately 6–9 individuals.\n\nDespite brief periods of slight population increase detected between ticks 1392–1623 and 1856–2087, the overall trajectory remains negative. The population median of approximately 1.5 individuals reflects the prolonged scarcity characteristic of the latter portion of the simulation. By tick 2311, the population reaches zero, indicating complete extinction of the prey species.\n\nWithin the context of the Megafaunal Hunting Pressure Model, this extinction pattern emerges from the interaction of constant predation pressure exerted by 20 immortal human hunters utilizing food storage and optimal foraging strategies within a 6-patch foraging radius, combined with prey sexual dimorphism (males: food value 30, processing cost 6; females: food value 27, processing cost 3) and environmental seasonality (0.8). The processing cost differential favoring females (3 versus 6) relative to their food value disadvantage (27 versus 30) creates complex prey choice scenarios, yet the mortality pressure exceeds the prey population's reproductive capacity given the birth spacing interval of 730 ticks and senescence onset at 7300 ticks. The rapid depletion from initial densities suggests that optimal foraging behavior by immortal hunter agents creates an unsustainable predation regime that overwhelms the megaherbivore herds' demographic resilience, driving the system irreversibly toward extinction despite temporary low-density fluctuations."
}

